## Architectural Principles — Hexagonal (Ports & Adapters)

### Core (the hexagon)
- The application core contains the **business logic** and exposes/consumes behavior exclusively through **ports** (interfaces).
- The core has **zero awareness** of how it is invoked or how it persists data — those are concerns of adapters.

### Ports
- **Inbound ports (driving):** the API the core offers to the outside (commands, queries, use cases).
- **Outbound ports (driven):** the contracts the core needs from the outside (repositories, gateways, message buses).
- Ports are **interfaces owned by the core**. Adapters implement them.

### Adapters
- **Driving adapters:** translate external triggers (HTTP, CLI, scheduled jobs, message consumers) into calls to inbound ports.
- **Driven adapters:** implement outbound ports against external systems (databases, third-party APIs, queues).
- Adapters are **swappable**: the core does not change when an adapter changes.

### Dependency Rule
Dependencies always point **toward the core**. Adapters depend on the core; the core depends on nothing external.

### Dependency Injection
Constructor injection for ALL dependencies — adapters are wired at composition root, never instantiated by the core.

## Key Conventions

- **Naming:** {{NAMING_CONVENTIONS}}
- **Imports:** core code never imports from `adapters/` or framework packages
- **Error handling:** {{ERROR_HANDLING_CONVENTIONS}} — domain errors defined in core; adapters translate technical failures into domain errors
- **Commits:** Conventional Commits (feat, fix, refactor, docs, test, chore)
- **Branching:** {{BRANCHING_STRATEGY}}
- **Testing:** core tested in isolation with fakes/stubs implementing outbound ports; adapters tested via contract tests against real or in-memory implementations of their port

